<div style="text-align: justify;">Albert Einstein discovered general
relativity in 1915 A.D. The principal idea in the relativity theory is
that the speed of light, which is 299792 kilometers per second, is an
absolute speed maximum and nothing can exceed this speed limit in the
universe. The relativity theory also states that anything which is
moving at the speed of light will move at the speed of light compared
to anything, which is moving slover than the speed of light. This means
that if you drove a car at speed say 120 kilometers per hour, which is
about 3 meters per second, and switch lights on, that light still has
the same speed of 299792000 meters per second and not 299792003 meters
per second nor 299791997 meters per second. How is this possible?<br>
